				<p>Concerns pertaining to a mission may be considered in four categories:  (1) Finances: Any expenses over and beyond what would have been needed at home may be subsidized by children, friends, quorums, or by other members of the family.  (2) Fear: Mature missionaries need not fear tracting or learning a new language. Much can be contributed using talents already acquired. Missionaries can venture into another language situation knowing that they will learn what they need to know without demanding fluency of themselves. They will learn some of their mission language and find joy in using each new expression.  (3) Fitness: While a risk-free environment cannot be guaranteed either at home or in the mission field, appropriate provisions can be made for proper diet and exercise. Routine needs for physical care can generally be met in the mission field. In the event of an emergency, evacuation, if advisable, is possible.  (4) Families: Children and grandchildren of senior missionaries will be blessed because of their service. To a missionary the Lord provided this promise: &ldquo;Behold, you have had many afflictions because of your family; nevertheless, I will bless you and your family, yea, your little ones; and the day cometh that they will believe and know the truth and be one with you in my church&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/31.2?lang=eng#1" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 31:2</a>). As those &ldquo;little ones&rdquo; pray for their missionary parents, they will be drawn toward the Lord as well as to parents or grandparents.</p>
